# Secure coding rules

## Baseline expectations
- Treat all inputs as untrusted; validate format, ranges, and size.
- Prefer safe defaults (HTTPS, strong crypto, least privilege).
- Do not expose internal errors or sensitive data in user-facing messages.
- Never include secrets, tokens, or credentials in code or output.

## Privacy defaults
- Offline-first: no network calls by default.
- No telemetry unless explicitly enabled, documented, and easily disabled.
- Limit file system scope to app directories.
- Sanitize user-provided paths before use.

## Data handling
- Use parameterized queries for any database access.
- Escape or encode user-controlled output when rendering or generating content.
- Avoid logging PII or sensitive identifiers.

## Dependency hygiene
- Prefer standard libraries or well-known, vetted dependencies.
- Do not introduce packages that are unverified or unused.
- Keep versions explicit and stable.

## Verification
- Add tests for security-critical paths, including negative tests.
- When changes are non-trivial, perform a self-review pass and fix issues found.
